				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">At some point you'll find the following code:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; ldx #5<br />loop:<br />&nbsp; stx $8000<br />&nbsp; lda $383,x<br />&nbsp; and #$1f<br />&nbsp; sta $8001<br />&nbsp; dex<br />&nbsp; bpl loop<br />&nbsp; rts<br /></div><br /><br />If you reason your way through it, you'll see that it copies the five bytes from [$383+x] to the N108 register #x<br /><br />It also specifically masks off the upper three bits of each write, which when you combine it with the write-up about how mapper 95 works, means that it's always forcing the nametables to &quot;1-screen A&quot;.<br /><br />And there's another loop that looks similar, but doesn't mask off the upper three bits.<br /><br />So this is where I did the same thing to find how the values got <em>in</em> to RAM at $383 through $388</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

